      <h3 id=home2>Dreamers will continue to live in fear and their legality will continue to be questioned in the courts unless Congress finally acts and creates a pathway to citizenship.<h3>

      <h2 class=home1>What is DACA?</h2>
      <p> DACA, or Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals, gives temporary protection from deportation and permission to work legally to an estimated 650,000 people who were brought to the United States as children. Recipients, otherwise known as Dreamers, must then apply for renewal every two years. To be eligible for DACA, you must have come to the US before your 16th birthday and have lived here since June 15, 2007; you must also be attending school, or a highschool graduate and not been convicted of certain crimes. The program was started by the Obama adminstration in 2012 and former President Donald Trump tried to get rid of the program in 2017 but was blocked by the Supreme Court last year since they had no "reasoned explanation for [their] action." </p>

      <iframe id=vid width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/R2iwHmOdzVU" title="YouTube video player" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

      <p id=homeP>Dreamers have made grand contributions to the U.S. economy, communities, and schools as well as serving in our armed forces and working at the frontlines during the peak of the covid pandemic. Most people were brought to the U.S. at a very young age thus the only home they've truly know is the States, not the country they were born in. The inhumanity of preventing hundreds of thousands of people from becoming full members of our society must come to a stop. Congress must take action and provide a permanent solution by granting a path to citizenship for all Dreamers. </p>

